VISUALIZATION

  1. Three critiques of the graphic:

  1. This graph requires the viewer to compare areas between the bubbles, which is difficult. This problem is somewhat mitigated by the percentages printed on the bubbles.

  2. The color choices on this graph seem to be completely random. It is unclear why the age group bubbles don’t have color but the gender group bubbles do.

  3. If the text were bigger/bolder, it would draw attention better to the information the graph intends to convey. The names of the groups do not stand out as clearly as would be ideal.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=cut, y=carat)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=color), position = "identity") + 
  xlab("CUT OF DIAMOND") + 
  ylab("CARAT OF DIAMOND") + 
  coord_flip()

  1. It is much easier to visualize and compare the distributions of the carat variable for each combination of diamond cut and color if the graph uses the “dodge” position instead of “identity.”
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=cut, y=carat)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=color), position = "dodge") + 
  xlab("CUT OF DIAMOND") + 
  ylab("CARAT OF DIAMOND") + 
  coord_flip()

  1. Here is the code that adds a new column to the diamonds data set called price_per_carat that shows the price of each diamond per carat.
diamonds %>% mutate(price_per_carat = price/carat)
  1. The output below shows how many diamonds of each cut there are total, and also how many and what proportion of these have a price > 10,000 and a carat < 1.5.

The results make sense. Only a tiny proportion of the diamonds in the dataset are both relatively small (<1.5 carats) and also relatively expensive (>$10,000). However, a higher proportion of the better cut diamonds fall into this category than the poorer cut diamonds.

The number of diamonds that meet the >$10,000 & <1.5 carat requirements in each group may be misleading because the total number of diamonds in each group varies so much. But the proportion of diamonds that meet the requirements accounts for the differences in group size.

diamonds %>% group_by(cut) %>% 
  summarize(
    total_count = n(),
    group_count = sum(price > 10000 & carat < 1.5),
    group_proportion = mean(price > 10000 & carat < 1.5)
  )

  1. Looking at only the cities and months with greater than 500 sales:
bigsales <- txhousing %>% rename(med_price = median) %>% filter(sales > 500)
  1. The distributions of the median sales price when grouped by city differ quite a bit. See below.
# This table shows that the city with the highest median price was Collin County ($196,000), 
# and the city with the lowest median price was Ft. Worth ($114,600). 
bigsales %>% group_by(city) %>% 
  summarize(median_price = median(med_price)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(median_price))

# These histograms of the distribution of median prices by city vary a lot in shape. 
# For example, Bay Area is unimodal and nearly symmetrical, Dallas is unimodal and skews right,
# and Austin is bimodal.
ggplot(bigsales, aes(x = med_price)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap(~ city) 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# These boxplots are another visualization of the distribution of median sales prices for 
# each city, and they also show a lot of variation. For example, the lower two quartiles of 
# El Paso median prices cover a much wider spread than the upper two quartiles, 
# while Denton County is the opposite.
ggplot(bigsales) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = reorder(city, med_price, FUN = median), y = med_price)) +
  xlab("CITY") + 
  ylab("MEDIAN SALES PRICE") + 
  coord_flip()

  1. I would be curious to investigate Austin further to try to understand its bimodal distribution of median prices. Maybe housing prices shot up suddenly at some point, or crashed? I’d also like to understand why the cities with the highest median sales prices (Collin County, Austin, Montgomery County, Fort Bend) also seem to have the greatest range in their upper quartile median prices. This really contrasts with El Paso, a city with a low median and very little range in its upper quartile median prices.

  2. The smaller the number of observations in a group, the less meaningful measures of center like median are. That might be a reason to filter out all cities and months with sales less than 500.
